history.content:
It's very rare that EECS dept upper divs block enrollment thru CalCentral for not completing prereqs (i.e. no hard prereqs).

Second anon: Prereqs aren't enforced. Just make sure you know linear algebra -- that's the actual thing you need to know before the course. And it would be a big plus to also already know Singular Value Decomposition (SVD), Principal Component Analysis (PCA), and Positive Semidefinite Matrices (PSD) --> as in, having done problems involving them and understanding what each one can do. Overall, it's a huge benefit to know Linear Algebra really, really well because the first 3rd of the semester is a review of linear algebra and super hard linear algebra homeworks, the likes of which have never been seen in ee16a or math 54...only maybe in math 110 which I haven't taken. Also, don't forget to search for more posts concerning ee127 and prereqs and info about the class :)
It's very rare that EECS dept upper divs block enrollment thru CalCentral for not completing prereqs (i.e. no hard prereqs).
It's very rare that EECS dept upper divs block enrollment thru CalCentral for missing prereqs (i.e. no hard prereqs).

Does anyone know how hard the prereqs for EE16A and EE16B are enforced for EE127? I haven't taken either yet. I'm taking 189 right now and I want to take EE127 to strengthen some of my concepts. I see that you can get consent from the instructor. How does that work exactly? Do I just email the professor showing interest in taking the course?
